{#
  A day's entries — included when a .cal-day cell is tapped, in both the
  month and week history views (see app.routes.web._build_history_context
  and components/history.html.jinja2's month/week branches).

  Each entry row has a stable .entry-row wrapper so the edit-in-place flow
  can swap it via hx-target="closest .entry-row" / hx-swap="outerHTML" — the
  same convention as components/period_log.html.jinja2.

  Context: day ("YYYY-MM-DD"), entries (hydrated entry dicts: id, occurred_at,
  time_known, memo, values, tags, comment_count). The day is already
  selected/shown in the heading, so only the time (when known) is shown per
  entry, not the date.

  Included `with context`, so it also relies on:
    activity_id        int          — owning activity (edit-route URLs)
    history.is_owner    bool         — pencil edit shown only when truthy
    history.can_comment bool         — comment toggle shown when this or
                                        entry.comment_count is truthy
    history.username    str | None   — comment toggle suppressed entirely
    history.slug         str | None   when either is None (e.g. a guest-owned
                                        activity with no public profile URL)
    history.expand_comment_entry_id  int | None — a `?c={entry_id}` deep-link
                                        target (notification click-through).
                                        The matching entry's comment toggle
                                        gets an extra `load` trigger so its
                                        thread auto-expands on render; every
                                        other entry's toggle stays click-only.
    history.login_redirect_url  str | None — an already-validated
                                        `/login?next=...` URL (see
                                        app/routes/public.py and
                                        app/routes/web.py::activity_history),
                                        set only for a real anonymous (no
                                        session) visitor on an otherwise-
                                        readable activity. When set, an entry
                                        with zero comments shows a "log in to
                                        comment" link instead of nothing
                                        (history.can_comment is False for that
                                        same anonymous viewer, so neither the
                                        toggle nor the composer would
                                        otherwise render). An entry that
                                        already has comments still shows the
                                        normal read-only toggle.

  An entry selected for a given day can also appear in the period's full
  chronological log (components/period_log.html.jinja2) on the same page,
  but since the Task 5 restructure the two are mutually exclusive (only one
  body state renders at a time) -- so both use the shared
  components/_entry_row.html.jinja2 macro, which emits the plain canonical
  `comment-slot-{{ entry.id }}` id in both places.
#}
{% from "components/_entry_row.html.jinja2" import entry_row %}

<div class="flex flex-col gap-2 rounded-card border border-border bg-surface-2 p-3">
    <h4 class="text-body font-medium text-text-primary">
        {{ strings.CALENDAR_DAY_ENTRIES_TITLE }} — {{ day }}
    </h4>
    {% if not entries %}
        <p class="text-caption text-text-muted">{{ strings.CALENDAR_DAY_ENTRIES_EMPTY }}</p>
    {% else %}
        <ul class="flex flex-col gap-1">
            {% for entry in entries %}
                {{ entry_row(
                    entry,
                    activity_id,
                    is_owner=history.is_owner,
                    can_comment=history.can_comment,
                    username=history.username,
                    slug=history.slug,
                    expand_comment_entry_id=history.expand_comment_entry_id,
                    login_redirect_url=history.login_redirect_url,
                ) }}
            {% endfor %}
        </ul>
    {% endif %}
</div>
